## {{ rule.title }}

The U.S.-Germany income tax treaty ([DBA-USA Article 10](https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-trty/germtech.pdf)) sources dividends paid by a U.S. corporation to U.S. source. For a U.S. citizen who is a German tax resident, those dividends are taxable by both countries — and IRS Publication 514's *treaty re-sourcing* worksheet is the mechanism that determines how much additional U.S. foreign tax credit can be claimed to avoid double taxation. This rule graph (TREATY25-15 through TREATY25-18) executes that worksheet.

This stage performs [Pub. 514](https://www.irs.gov/publications/p514) worksheet line 15: subtract the foreign-source dividend split from the total dividend totals to get the U.S.-source slice.

For 2025:

- **U.S.-source ordinary dividends** (worksheet line 15a): **{{ rule.outputs[0].value | money(currency="USD") }}**
- **U.S.-source qualified dividends** (worksheet line 15b): **{{ rule.outputs[1].value | money(currency="USD") }}**

If both numbers are zero, there is nothing for the treaty worksheet to act on; later stages will produce zero additional FTC. The same numbers are also surfaced into the U.S. graph at US25-15 so the U.S.-side flow can consume them without crossing the treaty graph boundary.

